subject: HISTORY
text: What evidence can you produce for and against the view that the Roman occupation of Britain was chiefly military?

subject: HISTORY
text: Estimate the importance in Scottish history of the reign of David I.

subject: HISTORY
text: Examine the claims of Edward I to be the greatest of the Plantagenets.

subject: HISTORY
text: Account for the outbreak of the Wars of the Roses and for the victory of Henry Tudor.

subject: HISTORY
text: Write notes on two of the following: the Synod of Whitby, the Danelaw, Harold Godwineson, St. Anselm, the Lollards, the relations of James II with the House of Douglas.

subject: HISTORY
text: "The Reformation in England was effected by the Crown, that in Scotland against the Crown." How far is this true?

subject: HISTORY
text: Account for the increasing English hostility to Spain in the reign of Elizabeth Tudor, and state how far the aims of the English were achieved during that reign.

subject: HISTORY
text: What were the chief grievances of the Long Parliament when it met in (1640), and how far were they remedied before the outbreak of the Civil War?

subject: HISTORY
text: Trace the relations of Charles II with France, explaining how far his policy was unpopular with his people.

subject: HISTORY
text: To what extent is it true to say that the English desired the Union of (1707) but that the Scots did not?

subject: HISTORY
text: "A great minister in home affairs but inept in foreign affairs." Discuss this estimate of Walpole.

subject: HISTORY
text: What were the chief developments in the textile industries during the eighteenth century, and what were their social effects?

subject: HISTORY
text: How far was there an "enlightened toryism" in the reign of George IV?

subject: HISTORY
text: Explain the causes of the Crimean War and discuss the way in which it was conducted by Britain.

subject: HISTORY
text: "My mission is to pacify Ireland." What did Gladstone do to fulfil this mission, and with what degree of success or failure?

subject: HISTORY
text: How far is it true to say that British foreign policy underwent a revolution in the early years of the twentieth century?

subject: HISTORY
text: Explain the chief steps towards Canadian self-government between the Peace of Paris (1763) and the British North America Act (1867), and describe briefly the circumstances in which they were taken.

subject: HISTORY
text: Describe and compare the social and political effects on South Africa of the discovery of diamonds and of the gold rush to the Transvaal.

subject: HISTORY
text: Write notes on two of the following: the Stamp Act of (1765), Horatio (Viscount Nelson), Dr. Thomas Chalmers, the Anti-Corn Law League, Charles Darwin, the formation of the Labour Party.
